INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT (WEDNESDAY)

The barn, half empty still. Where the simulator stood: the same clean rectangle of dust. Cricket sits at the workbench with just the radio now, no panel, no couch, no window. He keys the mic.

CRICKET:
Net's open.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Copy.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
About time.

A silence on the net that isn't the usual silence.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
I did two years on a boomer off Adak listening for Soviet screws, so men like Earl could keep a barn a Russian couldn't touch. And a fella in a zip-up vest walks in with a sticker gun.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Say the word, Gunny. You've been chewing on it since Tuesday.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Commies. That's the word. Don't care what flag they're flying over the building. That's what they are, and we used to know what to do about that.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
(quiet, to no one in particular)
NASA was going to scrap that trainer in seventy-five. Cut it for aluminum. I drove a horse trailer to Houston and asked a supply captain if anybody'd miss it. He said the paperwork was eight months backed up, and if the truck showed up empty, that's what the truck would show.
(beat)
Fifty years I kept government property safe for the government. They sent a man to take it back like I stole it.

CRICKET:
And do what. Burn something down. I've got a grandson.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Nobody said burn anything down.

CRICKET:
Then what did you say.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Compliance office closes at five. Empty gravel lot out back, faces the highway. Fourth of July's been illegal going on seven months now — no sale, no discharge, not even in your own yard.

STITCH (FILTERED):
You're the one's still got a barn to launch from, Earl. Rest of us are three counties over.

CRICKET:
So I'm the one climbing a fence at my age.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Didn't say climb a fence. Say it's a strip mall with a flagpole and an empty lot. Pull up, light it, pull out.

CRICKET:
And if I get picked up.

GUNNY (FILTERED):
Then you got picked up for fireworks, same as half this country used to, every summer, before somebody made it a federal matter.

Silence on the net. Cricket looks at the dust rectangle, the bare bolt holes, the empty bench where the panel used to sit.

CRICKET:
(finally)
...Man my age, about to get arrested for fireworks.

STITCH (FILTERED):
Man my age used to get arrested for a lot worse than fireworks.

CRICKET:
(the ghost of something almost like a laugh)
That so.

A beat.

CRICKET:
Alright. Let's do it.

DUTCH (FILTERED):
God willing.

Cricket keys the mic twice — two clicks. Two clicks come back. Then two more. Then two more.

CUT TO:
